<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1113]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1051,1077]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yin" authorityYear="2022" box="[563,673,1051,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Arthromelodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulatus">
<emphasis box="[563,673,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">angulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, - 
<emphasis box="[697,711,1051,1076]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">a</emphasis>
, - 
<emphasis box="[735,769,1051,1076]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">um</emphasis>
’ is a Latin adjective meaning ‘cornered, angular’, referring to the laterally expanded male tergite 1 (IV) of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
